		<part id="apis">
			<title>APIs Matter</title>
			<slide id="apis-data">
				<title>APIs ⊃ Data</title>
				<ul>
					<li>Data is information at rest, APIs are for interactions</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Good APIs are designed with interactions in mind</li>
					</ul>
					<li><em>Data-oriented APIs</em> can be mechanically derived from data models</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Basic interactions such as getting and changing/adding data</li>
					</ul>
					<li><em>Process-oriented</em> APIs are based on scenarios and user needs</li>
					<ul>
						<li>What problems do users have and which services help them best?</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="apis-are-different">
				<title>Where APIs are Different</title>
				<ul>
					<li>APIs are continuously consumed services</li>
					<li>API consumers should be able to rely on the API contract</li>
					<ul>
						<li><em>Loose coupling</em> allows consumers to keep doing what they are doing</li>
					</ul>
					<li>API producers can improve their products based on usage and feedback</li>
					<ul>
						<li><em>Designing for change</em> allows producers to keep improving the API landscape</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
		</part>
